{{about|the comedian|the baseball umpire|Mike Winters}} {{Infobox person | name = Mike Winters | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Michael Weinstein | birth_date = {{birth date|1926|11|15|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Islington]], [[London]], England | death_date = {{death date and age|2013|08|24|1926|11|15|df=y}} | death_place = [[Gloucestershire]], England | known_for = Partnership with [[Bernie Winters]] | education = | employer = | occupation = Comedian, musician, businessman, writer | title = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Mike Winters''', born '''Michael Weinstein''' (15 November 1926 – 24 August 2013),<ref name="DTO" /> was an English comedian, musician, businessman and writer who was the [[Straight man (stock character)|straight man]] of the comedy double act [[Mike & Bernie Winters]] with his younger brother, [[Bernie Winters|Bernie]].<ref name="DTO">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/10266468/Mike-Winters.html Daily Telegraph Obituary]. Retrieved 27 August 2013</ref>
==Early life==
He was born in [[Islington]], [[North London]], where his father was a [[bookmaker]]. Mike won a scholarship to [[Tottenham Grammar School]] but was evacuated to Wiltshire with his younger brother where he eventually ended up at the [[City of Oxford High School]] for Boys. At 15 Winters won a scholarship and grant to the [[Royal Academy of Music]] to study clarinet, where he was one of the founders of the Royal Academy of Music Jazz Quintet.<ref name="youtube.com">{{YouTube|0kzsKTfFNvU}}</ref> In [[World War II]], Winters, underage, was in the merchant navy.<ref name="youtube.com"/> Following a medical discharge due to [[sinusitis]] he enlisted in the [[Royal Canadian Legion|Canadian Legion]] as a musician, reaching the rank of captain. He then played [[jazz]] with his brother on drums and performed as a musician at dances and weddings. In 1964 Winters and his brother were inducted into the show business fraternity, the [[Grand Order of Water Rats]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gowr.co.uk/all-water-rats/v/42|title=Biography of a Water Rat|publisher=}}</ref> Winters was the owner of a 1965 [[Alvis Car and Engineering Company|Alvis]] TE21 sports coupe in white, which he purchased at the Earls Court Motorshow.
==Solo career==
After the [[Mike & Bernie Winters|double act with his brother]] ended in 1978, Winters moved to [[Florida]] because his wife suffered from arthritis.<ref name="youtube.com"/> Winters opened the first theatre club in Miami and worked with legendary boxing manager, [[Angelo Dundee]], presenting black-tie boxing events. Winters was also active in charity work, with visits to Miami from [[Muhammad Ali]], [[Prince Michael of Kent]] and [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Prince Edward]] and was awarded the city of Miami keys by the mayor. Winters also co-produced with Jude Parry, directed, performed and wrote the first British professional pantomime to appear in Florida, it was such a success that they continued for five years, starring not only local young talent but also [[Davy Jones (musician)|Davy Jones]] of the [[The Monkees|Monkees]].<ref name="youtube.com"/>
==Writer== He published five books including a biography of Angelo Dundee and ''The Axis of Greatness'' about the relationship between Angelo and his boxers [[Sugar Ray Leonard]] and Muhammad Ali. His two novels are ''Miami One Way'' and ''Razor Sharp'' and his last book was a light-hearted memoir called ''The Sunny Side Of Winters''.
